{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507810"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2676"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2676"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.05,0.03,0.15,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82728"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2676"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67863"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44527"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82728"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man is being counselled about his suitability for bariatric surgery in the management of his obesity. His BMI is currently 37 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E and despite various dietary modification, he has not been able to get his BMI below the obese range. His medical history includes hypertension, gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, type 2 diabetes and an episode of ureteric colic two years earlier. His medications includes lisinopril, amlodipine, rabeprazole, metformin and semaglutide. He is a lifetime non-smoker and drinks two glasses of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe merits of Roux-en-Y gastric bypass or a sleeve gastrectomy are discussed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the strongest contraindication to him undergoing a sleeve gastrectomy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type 2 diabetes","Renal calculus disease","Hypertension","Alcohol consumption","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe indications for bariatric surgery are based on a person\u2019s BMI (body mass index), which needs to be 40 or greater to be considered or greater than 35 with a co-morbid conditions such as type 2 diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, obstructive sleep apnea, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, among others. In his case he has a BMI of 37 plus co-morbid conditions of type 2 diabetes and hypertension make him a candidate for bariatric surgery. His \u003Cstrong\u003Etype 2 diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertension\u003C/strong\u003E are not contraindications to the surgery but rather they are indications in his case. In addition to this the patient must have failed non-operative weight loss attempts, been cleared by a psychologist/psychiatrist and be able to give their informed consent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome general contraindications to consider for any bariatric surgery include severe heart failure, unstable heart disease, end-stage lung disease, cancer or liver disease and drug/alcohol addiction/dependence. Additionally, the surgery requires general anaesthetic and hence the patient must be suitable for this. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite drug/alcohol dependence being a contraindication, his current \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E does not place him in the category of addiction or dependence. He should be advised about the current alcohol guidelines and the importance of alcohol-free days as well as the benefits of reducing alcohol consumption, which includes weight loss. Hence, this is not a contraindication in his case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive renal calculi would be a factor in delaying elective surgery such as bariatric, but his history of \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal calculus disease\u003C/strong\u003E two years prior does not influence his suitability for the surgery now. Undergoing the surgery can place the body under stress and cause dehydration, which can precipitate stone formation, so this may be taken into consideration by the anaesthetist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA contraindication to sleeve gastrectomy is \u003Cstrong\u003Egastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD)\u003C/strong\u003E, as this type of bariatric procedure can worsen the reflux and increase the risk of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. Sleeve gastrectomy is a procedure to remove a large portion of the stomach (around the greater curvature) to reduce the size of the stomach. As can be imagined with a reduced stomach capacity reflux worsens in these individuals as there is both less room in the stomach for acidic contents to go as well as reduced cells able to produce bicarbonate and other anti-reflux products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERoux-en-Y gastric bypass surgery involves reducing the size of the stomach to a small pouch and connecting this directly onto the small intestine. This procedure has been determined to be the most effective bariatric surgery in terms of both weight loss and improvement of reflux symptoms. Hence, if he were to undergo a type of bariatric surgery this would be the ideal procedure for him. Compared to sleeve gastrectomy which has been shown to worsen already existing disease and even increase the incidence of disease in previously unaffected individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["GORD is a contraindication for a sleeve gastrectomy.","In a patient with GORD Roux-en-Y gastric bypass is the best option for bariatric surgery.","The indications for bariatric surgery include a BMI \u003E40 or BMI \u003E35 + co-morbid conditions."],"references":["Stahl JM, Malhotra S. Obesity Surgery Indications And Contraindications. In: StatPearls [Internet]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513285/","El-Hadi M, Birch DW, Gill RS, Karmali S. The effect of bariatric surgery on gastroesophageal reflux disease. Can J Surg. 2014;57(2):139-144. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3968207/","Bou Daher H, Sharara AI. Gastroesophageal reflux disease, obesity and laparoscopic sleeve gastrectomy: The burning questions. World J Gastroenterol. 2019 Sep 7;25(33):4805-4813. doi: 10.3748/wjg.v25.i33.4805. PMID: 31543675; PMCID: PMC6737315. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6737315/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67863"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2676"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67863"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T21:39:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T21:41:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2676"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82728"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type"